  ('goblet-squat', 'The dumbbell load gives the athlete a scalable resistance problem while each limb, joint, and trunk position must organize independently. This develops usable force production without needing high impact or jump-based explosiveness.', 'Belongs in Capacity because the main adaptation is strength, force tolerance, and structural reserve. It can support later explosiveness when reps are coached with intent, but it should not replace true Output work.', 'Use in the Capacity phase after Prepare/Access and any true Output work. Keep it before hard conditioning; pair with longer rest when strength or high-intent concentric speed is the goal.', 'The most common mistake is turning a strength lift into a rushed fatigue circuit or over-tagging it as explosiveness simply because the athlete moves hard. Keep load, tempo, rest, and technique aligned with strength first.', 'Scale by load, range of motion, stance support, tempo, set length, and rest. Progress only when posture, pain-free range, and repeatable rep quality are stable.'),
